  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RevPAR acceleration:</strong> If business travel and group bookings grow faster than anticipated.</li>
    <li><strong>Loyalty program leverage:</strong> The Marriott Bonvoy program continues to drive direct bookings, improving margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Unit growth:</strong> Faster-than-expected pipeline conversion into actual rooms.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt load:</strong> Marriott carries significant debt. Rising refinancing costs could eat into cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Macroeconomic sensitivity:</strong> Travel is highly cyclical. A global recession would drastically impact RevPAR and franchise fees.</li>
    <li><strong>Competition:</strong> Airbnb and other alternative lodging options could cap pricing power.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Marriott's debt so high?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Marriott operates an asset-light model, meaning they franchise the brand rather than owning the real estate. However, they still carry significant corporate debt, much of it taken on during acquisitions (like Starwood) or to survive pandemic disruptions. The debt is manageable due to their highly predictable franchise fee income, but it still negatively impacts the equity value in a DCF.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the asset-light model impact valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">An asset-light model requires very little capital expenditure to grow. When a new hotel opens, the franchisee pays for the building, while Marriott just collects a percentage of top-line revenue. This leads to strong free cash flow conversion, which is very favorable for a DCF valuation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Always conduct your own due diligence.</div>
    </details>
